      Be sure to try each question before looking at the solutions.
    </p>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-f25exam1">
    <title>Questions</title>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-f25-q1">
<statement>
   Scientists are monitoring ground elevation near a volcano to detect signs of potential eruption. The elevation
   <m>
       h(t)
   </m>
   , in meters, is measured at regular intervals of time
   <m>
       t
   </m>
   , in days.

  <table xml:id="VolcanoExam1F25q1" >
        <title>Ground elevation near a volcano.</title>
    <tabular halign="center">
      <row>
        <cell><p><m>t</m> (days)</p></cell>
        <cell><p><m>h</m> (m)</p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p>0</p></cell>
        <cell><p>1200.0</p></cell>
      </row>
            <row>
        <cell><p>2</p></cell>
        <cell><p>1200.8</p></cell>
      </row>
            <row>
        <cell><p>4</p></cell>
        <cell><p>1201.7</p></cell>
      </row>
            <row>
        <cell><p>6</p></cell>
        <cell><p>1202.5</p></cell>
      </row>
            <row>
        <cell><p>8</p></cell>
        <cell><p>1203.0</p></cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>
  </table>
<ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
    <p>
      Estimate
      <m>
          h'(6)
      </m>
      using a central difference. Be sure to include units on your response.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Does
      <m>
          h''(6)
      </m>
      appear to be positive or negative? Explain.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      What are the units on
      <m>
          h''(6)
      </m>
      ? In words, interpret the meaning of the value of
      <m>
          h''(6)
      </m>
      .
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
</statement>
<answer>
<ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>h'(6) \approx \frac{1203.0-1201.7}{8-4} = 0.325</m> meters per day
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>h''(6)</m> appears to be negative since the rate of increase of <m>h</m> seems to be decreasing at <m>t=6</m> days.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>\frac{\frac{meters}{day}}{day}</m>; this is the rate at which the rate of height increase each day, increases
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
</answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-f25-q2">
<statement>
        On <xref ref="Exam1F25q2pic"/> draw the graph of a function <m>f(x)</m> for which
        <ol marker="(i)">
        <li> <m>f(-2)&lt;0</m>, </li>
        <li> <m>f'(-2)&lt;0</m>, </li> 
        <li> <m>f''(-2)=0</m>, and </li>
        <li> the average rate of change of <m>f</m> on the interval <m>[-2,1]</m> is
        zero. </li>
        </ol>
        Clearly label values of points on the graph at <m>x=-2</m> and <m>x=1</m>.
    <figure xml:id="Exam1F25q2pic">
  <caption>Graph a function <m>f(x)</m> meeting the required conditions.</caption> 
  <image xml:id="Exam1F25q2picA" width="50%" >
<description>An empty coordinate axes system.
</description>
    <latex-image>
 \begin{tikzpicture}[thick,scale=1] [domain=-3:3]
\draw[step=1cm,color=gray!25] (-4,-4) grid (4,4);
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.5pt,-latex] (0,0) -- (4,0) node [below] at (3.5,0) {$x$};
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.5pt,-latex] (0,0) -- (-4,0);
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.5pt,-latex] (0,0) -- (0,4) node [right] at (0,3.5) {$y$};
   \draw [black!80,line width=0.5pt,-latex] (0,0) -- (0,-4);
%%  node[above] at (2,1) {$f(3,y)$};
\foreach \x/\xtext in { -3/-3, -1/-1, 1/1, 3/3}
    \draw[shift={(\x,0)}] (0pt,3pt) -- (0pt,-3pt) node[below] {$\xtext$};
\foreach \y/\ytext in { -3/-3, -1/-1, 1/1, 3/3}
   \draw[shift={(0,\y)}] (-2pt,0pt) -- (2pt,0pt) node[left] {$\ytext$};
\end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
  </image>
</figure>
</statement>
<answer>
  <p>
    Answers will vary.  However, they all will have the same <m>y</m>-coordinate at <m>x=2</m> and <m>x=1</m>.  And, they will be below the <m>x</m>-axis, decreasing, and likely changing concavity at <m>x=2</m>.   
  </p>
</answer>
 </exercise>

 <exercise xml:id="exam1-f25-q3">
<statement>
  <p>
    The temperature
    <m>
        T
    </m>
    (measured in
    <m>
        ^{\circ}F
    </m>
    ) of a cup of coffee at time
    <m>
        t
    </m>
    minutes after it is poured into a coffee cup is given by
    <md>
        T(t) = A + Be^{-ct}
    </md>
    where
    <m>
        A&gt;0
    </m>
    ,
    <m>
        B&gt;0
    </m>
    , and
    <m>
        c&gt;0
    </m>
    are constants. 
  </p>
  <ol marker="(a)">
    <li>
      <p>
        What are the units of
        <m>
            A
        </m>
        and
        <m>
            B
        </m>
        ?
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        What are the units of
        <m>
            c
        </m>
        ?
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        What are the units of
        <m>
            T'(t)
        </m>
        ? In words, what does the value
        <m>
            T'(10)
        </m>
        represent?
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Do you expect
        <m>
            T''(10)
        </m>
        to be positive, negative, or zero? Why?
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</statement>
<answer>
  <p>
    <ol marker="(a)">
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>^{\circ}F</m>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          per minute
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{^{\circ}F}{minute}</m>; <m>T'(10)</m> represents the rate at which the coffee increases in temperature 10 minutes after it is poured.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>T''(10)&gt;0</m> since the graph of <m>T(t)</m> is decreasing but concave up.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>
</answer>
 </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="exam1-f25-q4">
<statement>
  <p>
    For which of the graphs shown in <xref ref="F26Ex1q4"/> does
    <m>
        \displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow 3}f(x)
    </m>
    exist?
  </p>
  <figure xml:id="F26Ex1q4">
  <caption> Where does
    <m>
        \displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow 3}f(x)
    </m>
    exist?</caption> 
  <image source="images/Limitx3.jpg" width="90%">
        <description>
Three graphs labeled I, II, and III, each showing behavior near x = 3.

I. An increasing curve with a hole at x = 3 and y about 1.5. The curve approaches the hole from both sides.

II. Two separate curve pieces. As x approaches 3 from the left, the graph approaches y about 1; as x approaches 3 from the right, the graph approaches y about 2.

III. A smooth curve with a hole at (3, 1) and a filled point at (3, 2). The curve approaches y = 1 from both sides, but the function value at x = 3 is 2.

</description>
      </image>
</figure>
</statement>
<choices multiple-correct="yes" randomize="no">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>I</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>II</p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>III</p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

  </choices>
  </exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-f25-q5">
<statement>
The derivative of some function
<m>
  f
</m>
at some location
<m>
  x=a
</m>
is given by the value of
<md>
  \lim_{h \rightarrow 0}\frac{e^{-1-h}-e^{-1}}{h}.
</md>
Identify
<m>
  f(x)
</m>
and the value of
<m>
  a
</m>
.
</statement>
  <answer>
    <p>
      <m>f(x)=e^{-x}</m> and <m>a=1</m>
    </p>
  </answer>
  </exercise>

