<exercise xml:id="exam1-f25-q8">
<statement>
[Yes, this involves the absolute value!] Suppose that
<md>
    f(x) = \left| -x^{2}+2x+3\right|.
</md>
Use the
<em>
    limit definition of derivative
</em>
to find the value of the derivative
<m>
    f'(2)
</m>
. Be sure to use appropriate limit notation. Solutions using other methods will not receive credit.
</statement>
<answer>
  <p>
    <m>\displaystyle f'(2) = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{f(2+h)-f(2)}{h}</m> where <m>f(2)=|(-2)^2 + 2(2)+3| = 3</m>.  So, we have <md>
      <mrow> f'(2) \mathstrut \amp = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{ |-(2+h)^2 + 2(2+h)+3| - 3}{h} </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{ -(2+h)^2 + 2(2+h)+3 - 3}{h} </mrow> 
    </md>
    since <m>-(2+h)^2 + 2(2+h)+3 \approx 3 &gt; 0</m> for <m>h</m> small.  So, <md> 
      <mrow> f'(2) \mathstrut \amp = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{-4 - 4h - h^2 + 4 + 2h + 3 -3}{h} </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{h(-2-h)}{h} </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = -2 - h </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = -2 </mrow>
    </md>
  </p>
</answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-f25-q9">
<statement>
In <xref ref="F25Ex1q9"/> is the graph of <m>
    f(x)
</m>
.
<figure xml:id="F25Ex1q9">
  <caption> Which is a possible graph of <m>f'(x)</m>?</caption> 
  <image source="images/OriginalFunctionEx1F25.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>Graph of a curve that rises rapidly from below the x-axis, reaches a maximum near x = 1, then gradually decreases while remaining above the x-axis.
</description>
      </image>
</figure>
Which of the following is a possible graph of
<m>
    f'(x)
</m>
?
</statement>
<choices randomize="no">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <figure xml:id="F25Ex1q9OptA">
  <caption> Option A</caption> 
  <image source="images/OriginalFunctionEx1F25A.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>Graph of a curve that decreases steeply, crosses the x-axis, reaches a shallow minimum, and then rises gradually toward zero.
</description>
      </image>
</figure>
      </statement>
            <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <figure xml:id="F25Ex1q9OptB">
  <caption> Option B</caption> 
  <image source="images/OriginalFunctionEx1F25B.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>Graph of a curve that decreases rapidly, crosses the x-axis near x = 0, reaches a minimum, and then slowly rises toward zero.
</description>
      </image>
</figure>
      </statement>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <figure xml:id="F25Ex1q9OptC">
  <caption> Option C</caption> 
  <image source="images/OriginalFunctionEx1F25C.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>Graph of a decreasing curve that remains above the x-axis and approaches zero as x increases.
</description>
      </image>
</figure>
      </statement>
    </choice>

     <choice>
      <statement>
        <figure xml:id="F25Ex1q9OptD">
  <caption> Option D</caption> 
  <image source="images/OriginalFunctionEx1F25D.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>Graph of a curve that rises to a maximum near x = 0, then decreases while remaining above the x-axis.
</description>
      </image>
</figure>
      </statement>

    </choice>

     <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>None of these. It looks like...</p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-f25-q11">
<statement>
For the graph of
<m>
    y=f(x)
</m>
given in <xref ref="F25Ex1q11"/>, find all  values of
<m>
    a
</m>
in the interval
<m>
    (-4,4)
</m>
for which
<m>
    \displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow a}f(x)
</m>
does not exist.
<figure xml:id="F25Ex1q11">
  <caption>For which <m>a</m> values does <m>
    \displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow a}f(x)
</m>
not exist? </caption> 
  <image source="images/LimitNotExistEx1F25.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>Graph with several pieces, including a decreasing line, an upper arc, an increasing line segment, and a decreasing curve. Open and closed circles indicate holes and defined function values at several x-values.
</description>
      </image>
</figure>
</statement>
<answer>
  <p>
    <m>a=-1,1</m>
  </p>
</answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-f25-q13">
<statement>
<p>
    A scientist measures the temperature <m>T</m> (measured in kelvins) of a
    certain metal bar <m>t</m> seconds after heat is removed.
    The equation <md>\displaystyle T(t)=\frac{30}{e^{t}}+ 10e^{t}</md> models the
    data observed.
</p>

<p>
    The scientist also observes that the length <m>L</m> of the metal bar
    (measured in centimeters) depends on its temperature through the equation
    <md>\displaystyle L(T) = 0.01T^{3} + \frac{64000}{T}.</md>
</p>
<ol marker="(a)">
<li>
  <p>
    Explain the meaning of
    <m>
        T'(300)
    </m>
    in the context of this problem. Be sure to include units.
  </p>
</li>
<li>
  <p>
    Describe as precisely and specifically as you can what the quantity
    <m>
        \displaystyle Q=\frac{T(273)-T(152)}{121}
    </m>
    represents in the context of this problem.
  </p>
</li>
<li>
  <p>
    Do you expect
    <m>
        L'(400)
    </m>
    to be positive or negative? Why? What are the units for this value and what does the value of
    <m>
        L'(400)
    </m>
    physically represent?
  </p>
</li>
</ol>
</statement>
<answer>
<ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>T'(300)</m> gives the rate at which the temperature of the bar increases (in Kelvin per second) 300 seconds after the heat is removed. 
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      This is the average rate of change of the temperature of the bar between times 152 and 273 seconds (measured in Kelvin per second).  
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      I expect <m>L'(400)</m> to be positive since the length of bar should increase as it gets warmer.  Units are centimeters per Kelvin.  <m>L'(400)</m> represents the rate at which length of bar increases due to change in temperature at the instant the temperature of the bar is 400 Kelvin.  
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
</answer>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>
</handout>